19:34.965 --> 19:36.717
'Cause most of the world
doesn't even know it.

19:36.800 --> 19:38.886
-Doesn't know, yeah.
That's true.

19:38.969 --> 19:41.680
When I first moved to the States,
I made a dish.

19:41.763 --> 19:43.724
I did fried chicken and watermelon,

19:43.807 --> 19:46.226
and my husband is like,
"You cannot do that."

19:46.310 --> 19:48.187
He was like, "That is the most
racist thing you can do."

19:48.270 --> 19:50.522
And for me,
I didn't think it was offensive.

19:50.606 --> 19:51.857
It's one of those foods

19:51.940 --> 19:54.526
that has sort of stereotypically
been associated with us.

19:54.610 --> 19:57.779
Black people during slavery
were allowed to keep chickens

19:57.863 --> 19:59.740
when you couldn't keep cows and pigs.

19:59.823 --> 20:00.782
Yardbirds.
-Yeah, exactly.

20:00.866 --> 20:01.700
Right.

20:01.783 --> 20:04.369
So you're keeping chickens.
You're also able to sell them,

20:04.453 --> 20:07.581
sell chicken dinners et cetera
to raise money for your freedom,

20:07.664 --> 20:10.292
or if you're free already, it's a way
that you could earn a living.

20:10.375 --> 20:13.879
So that kind of association
between black folks and fried chicken

20:13.962 --> 20:15.881
<i>goes back because of that.</i>

20:20.636 --> 20:25.224
<i>One thing is for certain. People</i>
<i>love fried chicken, but it's like...</i>

20:27.184 --> 20:29.394
I didn't know about this stuff
with fried chicken.

20:30.229 --> 20:33.148
You're not supposed to link

20:33.232 --> 20:36.568
fried chicken,
watermelon and black people,

20:36.652 --> 20:38.612
or African American culture or history.

20:38.695 --> 20:40.239
