living in Japan,

30:45.844 --> 30:51.724
because that stereotype is taken so far
away from what it used to be.

30:51.808 --> 30:54.936
Yes, it was demeaning in the US,

30:55.019 --> 30:59.357
because that's what idiot people
thought that black people ate.

30:59.440 --> 31:01.484
And then you come to Japan and it's like,

31:01.568 --> 31:03.194
"Welcome to Japan.

31:03.278 --> 31:04.737
Would you like some fried chicken
and watermelon?"

31:04.821 --> 31:07.073
Oh, my God.
-But I do like it.

31:10.702 --> 31:15.373
Should people be eating fried chicken
without knowing the history behind it?

31:16.708 --> 31:18.835
Whether the meaning is known or not,

31:18.918 --> 31:20.879
it's knowing that when people walk
through these doors,

31:20.962 --> 31:23.339
what's most important is that they
can taste the love

31:23.423 --> 31:25.842
every single time
they taste. That's soul food.

31:26.384 --> 31:28.177
Why am I talking to you, man?

31:28.261 --> 31:29.888
-I don't know.

31:31.180 --> 31:32.849
Tennessee-style hot chicken.

31:35.894 --> 31:36.895
It's delicious.

31:36.978 --> 31:38.229
Thank you very much.

31:38.313 --> 31:40.565
Having lived here myself,
and being Korean...

31:41.316 --> 31:44.193
And Koreans, I've always felt,
historically in Japan,

31:44.277 --> 31:47.697
have been seen as second-class citizens,
for the most part.

31:47.780 --> 31:51.492
How does it feel to be
a black American in Japan?

31:51.576 --> 31:54.746
I found out that a lot of Japanese people
love black people.

31:54.829 --> 31:56.080
-Hmm.

31:56.164 --> 31:57.916
But as for the black community,

31:57.999 --> 32:03.796
it was always more, uh, Jamaican,
African and African American together.

32:03.880 --> 32:06.507
Half the people,
even Africans think I'm African.

32:06.591 --> 32:10.929
Do you wanna be, "No, I'm American."
Does that matter here?

32:14.974 --> 32:17.060
Probably a good thing.
I'm Canadian.

32:19.896 --> 32:22.523
This is the picture of America
that we enjoy seeing.

32:22.607 --> 32:26.527
Because so many different races
come here and they eat

32:26.611 --> 32:29.280
and, you know, we all just
enjoy each other's time.

32:29.364 --> 32:31.741
And that's it.
And that's the way it should be.

32:33.910 --> 32:38.081
<i>Introducing Chicken McNuggets.</i>

32:38.665 --> 32:41.376
<i>Ooh. McNuggets.</i>
<i>McDonald's...</i>

32:41.459 --> 32:42.877
Okay, so, the reason that I feel like

32:42.961 --> 32:46.089
you need to taste nuggets is that you
have a history of nugget-eating public...

32:46.172 --> 32:47.340
Of secret nugget eating.

32:47.423 --> 32:50.969
Uh, I do eat a lot of, like, trash food.

32:51.052 --> 32:52.553
Do you know
the origins of the nugget?

32:52.637 --> 32:54.806
There were a lot of studies
that were released in the '80s

32:54.889 --> 32:57.725
<i>about how beef is really bad for you</i>
<i>and people stopped going to McDonald's,</i>

32:57.809 --> 33:00.436
<i>and McDonald's wanted</i>
<i>to retain these customers,</i>

33:00.520 --> 33:03.898
<i>and so they had an idea that they would </i>
<i>use chicken to bring them back in,</i>

33:03.982 --> 33:06.901
<i>which was, like, you know, </i>
<i>a healthier, white meat.</i>

33:06.985 --> 33:10.154
<i>So McDonald's commissioned Tyson</i>
<i>to build a nugget for them.</i>

33:10.238 --> 33:12.198
<i>So Tyson makes</i>
<i>the McDonald's nugget?</i>

33:12.281 --> 33:14.951
<i>Yeah. It's, like, an incredibly</i>
<i>automated process.</i>

33:15.034 --> 33:17.578
<i>And when it comes out,</i>
<i>the chicken is cut out into the shapes,</i>

33:17.662 --> 33:18.663
<i>and they get frozen and shipped.</i>

33:18.746 --> 33:21.416
McDonald's claims that they have
four different shapes.

33:21.499 --> 33:23.376
The bell and the boot.

33:23.459 --> 33:27.422
Then it's the ball and the bow, but I mean
like, these all look like boots.

33:28.423 --> 33:30.425
<i>We have two batches</i>
<i>of nuggets ready.</i>

33:30.508 --> 33:31.509
<i>We have so many chicken nuggets</i>

33:31.592 --> 33:33.052
<i>and you guys are gonna cut this down</i>
<i>into, like,</i>

33:33.136 --> 33:34.262
a 30-second thing where I'm just going...

33:36.472 --> 33:37.765
<i>Do I need to do this with you, or--</i>

33:37.849 --> 33:38.975
<i>Yeah. You need to feed me.</i>

33:39.058 --> 33:42.061
-That's the gluten-free chicken nugget.

33:42.145 --> 33:46.190
It's very dry. Is there...
I should grab water, right?

33:46.274 --> 33:48.776
These nuggets
are shaped like dinosaurs.

33:48.860 --> 33:51.195
It's like spray foam
that's been flavored with chicken.

33:51.279 --> 33:53.489
Why are you throwing away
these perfectly good nuggets?

33:53.573 --> 33:57.035
This is the crucible
of your sadness here.

33:57.118 --> 33:58.578
These are the ones
you eat the most frequently?

33:58.661 --> 34:00.955
Some would call it sad, but, uh...
You know.

34:01.581 --> 34:05.376
They're so unoffensive that you could
scarf down 30.

34:06.461 --> 34:08.254
Cordon Bleu Chicken Poppers.

34:08.337 --> 34:10.840
-I just don't want to touch it.

34:10.923 --> 34:13.051
There's no resistance from any chicken.  Let's move on.
-To hell with that nugget.

34:17.722 --> 34:19.849
<i>I feel like nuggets </i>
<i>are a factory of regret.</i>

34:19.932 --> 34:22.477
How could they call
this chicken fry? Look.

34:22.560 --> 34:24.145
It's more like a finger.

34:24.228 --> 34:25.730
Wake up, people.

34:25.813 --> 34:26.981
These aren't chicken fries.
They're chicken fingers.

34:29.817 --> 34:31.152
<i>In summary...</i>

34:32.070 --> 34:34.072
-no one should eat chicken nuggets.

34:34.155 --> 34:38.034
Eat something else.
Just prepare a different thing.

34:38.117 --> 34:39.118
Thank you for doing this.

34:39.202 --> 34:41.454
-Sorry.
-No problem. Let's hug it out.

34:49.921 --> 34:52.924
<i>I just never expected</i>
<i>that you would live in Koreatown.</i>

34:53.007 --> 34:54.133
Uh-huh.

34:54.217 --> 34:57.303
And I feel like a real idiot for assuming

34:57.386 --> 35:00.306
that someone like you
would never live here.

35:00.389 --> 35:02.433
-That's okay.

35:02.517 --> 35:05.186
To assume is to make an ass
out of you and me.

35:05.269 --> 35:07.230
-So I guess you shouldn't assume anything.
-Yes.

35:07.313 --> 35:10.233
Yeah, I love living in Koreatown.

35:10.316 --> 35:14.946
<i>The food in Koreatown</i>
<i>is so goddamn good.</i>

35:15.029 --> 35:17.240
This is just the whole fried chicken,
it comes plain with no sauce.

35:17.323 --> 35:19.742
Would you say that
is a spatchcocked chicken?

35:19.826 --> 35:22.912
-It is a spatchcocked fried chicken.

35:22.995 --> 35:24.497
Without the bone in the center.

35:24.580 --> 35:27.166
I just wanted you to know
that I knew what spatchcock is.

35:27.250 --> 35:28.126
-It's a great name.

35:29.544 --> 35:31.212
This is delicious.
Mmm-hmm.

35:31.295 --> 35:34.966
Before the invention of
the modern-day Korean fried chicken,

35:35.049 --> 35:38.136
-this was Korean fried chicken.
Yeah. Exactly.

35:38.219 --> 35:40.638
-Oh, wow.

35:40.721 --> 35:42.265
Um, it's only just coated in flour.
It is.

35:42.348 --> 35:44.684
Flour, salt, pepper, that's it.

35:44.767 --> 35:46.102
And this restaurant
has been around how long?

35:46.185 --> 35:48.563
Um, since, like, the mid-'90s.

35:48.646 --> 35:49.939
Well before
the Korean fried chicken craze.

35:50.022 --> 35:52.191
-Exactly. So it's kinda one of the OGs.
Mmm.

35:52.275 --> 35:55.361
Hot wings. It's got, like, a sweet
and spicy sauce coated around it.

35:55.444 --> 35:57.613
People come in
mostly for this one now, right?

35:57.697 --> 36:00.116
Yeah.
-All right, I'm gonna eat the wing.

36:02.994 --> 36:04.370
Yeah, that's really good.

36:04.453 --> 36:07.999
Well, I like them both.

36:08.082 --> 36:10.251
It's hard to invent something new,

36:10.334 --> 36:13.963
and somehow the Koreans
invented a new kind of fried chicken.

36:14.046 --> 36:16.841
How would you describe... What's
the difference

36:16.924 --> 36:20.136
-It's a double-fried type of thing.
Uh-huh.

36:20.219 --> 36:23.264
<i>Very thin crust that shatters</i>
<i>when you bite into it,</i>

36:23.347 --> 36:27.101
<i>with a sweet soy glaze</i>
<i>or something that's really spicy.</i>

36:27.185 --> 36:30.813
The weird thing is, I have
a version of this in sandwich form.

36:30.897 --> 36:35.234
It's basically a spicy fried chicken
sandwich with Korean dressing on it.

36:35.318 --> 36:36.861
But I don't have a Korean name with it.

36:36.944 --> 36:38.779
So maybe I'm part of the problem
right now.

36:38.863 --> 36:39.947
Do you miss that?

36:40.031 --> 36:42.533
Like, is that a weird thing
about becoming a successful chef,

36:42.617 --> 36:44.535
-Very hot.

36:44.619 --> 36:46.037
I do miss it.

36:46.120 --> 36:47.914
-You're only worried about your station.
-Yeah.

36:47.997 --> 36:51.167
You know everything you need to do.
You can control it.

36:51.250 --> 36:52.627
When you're really good at your job,

36:52.710 --> 36:54.712
you can almost
intentionally get in the weeds.

36:54.795 --> 36:56.172
-Yeah.
-'Cause that's fun.

36:56.255 --> 36:57.256
Yeah, it's an interesting thing.

36:57.340 --> 37:01.636
Like, I don't get scared on set
to act anymore in the way that I used to.

37:01.719 --> 37:04.222
It's sort of like where you're
talking about mastering your station,

37:04.305 --> 37:07.183
where, when you first start,
it's completely overwhelming.

37:07.266 --> 37:09.602
You're fucking up all the time,
you're getting yelled at,

37:09.685 --> 37:12.063
and then at a certain point,
maybe you could go on autopilot?

37:12.146 --> 37:13.564
I don't know what's it like to be a cook.

37:13.648 --> 37:16.025
You can.
And that's where you get in trouble.

37:16.108 --> 37:18.736
If you're not nervous
or nauseous every day,

37:18.819 --> 37:21.614
-then you're gonna regress.
-Yeah.

37:21.697 --> 37:23.241
So there are a lot of similarities
in cooking and acting.

37:23.324 --> 37:24.450
I think there are.

37:24.533 --> 37:28.496
Because, like, this innovation happens
because someone does it every day.

37:28.579 --> 37:31.165
It's like, "Well, I can make this a little
bit better or a little bit different."

37:31.249 --> 37:32.583
And then it just keeps on going.

37:32.667 --> 37:34.418
Where do you think it's gonna go?

37:34.502 --> 37:38.089
If kimchi can become popular
in my lifetime,

37:38.172 --> 37:41.133
then anything can happen with Korean food.

37:41.217 --> 37:44.929
But I think it's inevitable that you're
gonna see Korean fried chicken

37:45.012 --> 37:49.267
-on menus at Ruby Tuesdays or TGI Fridays.
-Mmm-hmm.

37:49.350 --> 37:51.811
Um, I don't know how I feel about that.

37:53.729 --> 37:57.358
I think it's... One hand, it's fantastic,
and another hand, it makes me sad.

37:57.441 --> 37:59.235
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

37:59.318 --> 38:01.279
I guess that's the whole thing, right?

38:01.362 --> 38:05.408
-Yeah, progress.

38:09.495 --> 38:15.710
If I grew up in Nashville, and I ate
Bolton's fried chicken as a kid,

38:15.793 --> 38:18.504
and then I got into cooking,
and I left fine dining,

38:18.587 --> 38:20.172
and I wanted to open up a restaurant,

38:20.256 --> 38:24.760
my initial reaction, first thing,
'cause comedians or actors or writers,

38:24.844 --> 38:27.013
you always go
to your first things in your life.

38:27.096 --> 38:29.724
I'd probably be like, "Oh, I want to make
a fried chicken shop.

38:29.807 --> 38:32.143
And I want to do it
as a homage to Bolton's.

38:32.226 --> 38:36.314
I love it so much
and I respect it so much,

38:36.397 --> 38:39.233
I want to make
the best damn version possible."

38:42.403 --> 38:44.905
So, can you tell me a little
about the history of it?

38:44.989 --> 38:48.617
My father opened a meat and three
in Franklin, Cool Springs,

38:48.701 --> 38:53.039
kind of a south suburb of Nashville.
I started working with him out there.

38:53.122 --> 38:56.459
And so he'd go to Bolton's or Prince's
or Pepperfire, and he'd bring it back,

38:56.542 --> 38:59.086
and we just put together our own blend,
and then people started ordering it.

38:59.170 --> 39:01.297
<i>I think that's kind of when he realized </i>
<i>we had something.</i>

39:01.380 --> 39:04.258
And so it was kind of this sort of
falling back in love with something that,

39:04.342 --> 39:08.387
uh, you grew up eating and always knew
was very much a Nashville thing.

39:08.471 --> 39:10.348
<i>People are queued up outside.</i>

39:10.431 --> 39:11.474
<i>They love your restaurant,</i>

39:11.557 --> 39:14.810
<i>and from what I've tasted so far,</i>
<i>I want to crush this.</i>

39:15.686 --> 39:19.899
Another point is, are you aware
of what critics say about you guys?

39:19.982 --> 39:21.275
Yeah, yeah, yes.

39:21.359 --> 39:23.652
You guys are white guys
selling something

39:23.736 --> 39:26.864
that was based on something
that was not of your culture.

39:26.947 --> 39:30.910
Well, we're gonna do it right,
and we're gonna be respectful of it.

39:30.993 --> 39:34.246
And I don't think the way
that people may have

39:34.330 --> 39:36.874
20 years ago, 100 years ago,
200 years ago, so...

39:36.957 --> 39:42.880
Yeah, I have to live for today
and to try to be a good person.

39:42.963 --> 39:46.759
As someone that is crushing your food,
and loves your food...

39:46.842 --> 39:48.344
This is really good, man,
by the way.

39:48.427 --> 39:51.389
-Mmm-hmm.

39:51.472 --> 39:53.849
-But you do, and you do.
-Yeah.

39:54.517 --> 39:56.185
How do you be respectful?

39:57.061 --> 40:00.731
I can't tackle all
of the bigger stuff by myself,

40:00.815 --> 40:04.860
I just know that as long as
we're good sort of tenants of it, um,

40:04.944 --> 40:06.278
that's the best we can do.

40:06.362 --> 40:09.073
I'll always pay an homage to the Prince's

40:09.156 --> 40:10.991
and being able to tell
that story of Bolton's,

40:11.075 --> 40:15.871
and kinda the people that paved the way
before we ever were even thought of.

40:15.955 --> 40:18.374
You're adding value,
you're adding to the community,

40:18.457 --> 40:21.627
but what if you start killing
the very thing that inspired this?

40:21.710 --> 40:25.673
-You kill Prince's, you kill Bolton's.
Yeah, that's the scary part.

40:25.756 --> 40:29.427
When we take it on
as our obsession and passion,

40:29.510 --> 40:32.221
there's a lot of stuff that comes along
with that. You know?

40:32.304 --> 40:33.973
There's a lot of stuff
that comes along with that.

40:34.890 --> 40:38.185
And that's a lot more complex
than just cooking food.

40:38.269 --> 40:40.896
Stuff that on the front end,
you would have never thought about,

40:40.980 --> 40:43.023
'cause you just wanted
to make good food, right?

40:43.607 --> 40:47.278
Progress is change and change
is progress. You hope for the best.

40:47.361 --> 40:48.195
Right.

40:49.029 --> 40:51.699
Now, do you eat hot chicken
anywhere else outside of Bolton's?

40:51.782 --> 40:52.700
No.

40:52.783 --> 40:54.493
How do you feel about other establishments
selling hot chicken?

40:54.577 --> 40:56.829
I think everybody has something to offer.

40:56.912 --> 41:00.124
<i>Some people came in on a commercial end,</i>
<i>and benefited off of it.</i>

41:00.207 --> 41:03.252
But they don't have an idea
of what authentic hot chicken is,

41:03.335 --> 41:05.921
but they go for it, and to each his own.

41:06.005 --> 41:09.383
It cuts a little bit but, you know,
you just shake it off and go on.

41:09.467 --> 41:12.052
'Cause we know what we got,
we know what we do.

41:12.136 --> 41:16.390
Would you ever open up in a more
traditionally more affluent community?

41:16.474 --> 41:21.395
Yes, but everybody can't afford
that $4,000, $5,000 rent.

41:21.479 --> 41:23.939
I like Hattie B's. It's delicious.

41:24.607 --> 41:26.901
I think though, that one of the things is,

41:26.984 --> 41:31.780
you've never marketed for, intentionally,
a whiter, more affluent audience.

41:31.864 --> 41:33.240
That's what they come for though.

41:33.324 --> 41:36.202
They wanted a place
where they could feel comfortable

41:36.285 --> 41:38.829
and have beer and enjoy hot chicken.

41:38.913 --> 41:41.081
<i>And they jumped on the opportunity.</i>

41:41.165 --> 41:44.001
Do you begrudge them for that?
-No.

41:44.084 --> 41:48.422
I'm amazed that you're able to keep it
as calm and cool and loving as you are.

41:48.506 --> 41:51.884
Well, that comes from
just having love in your heart,

41:51.967 --> 41:54.178
and knowing when you do what's right,

41:54.261 --> 41:58.015
and do the best that you can do,
in what you do,

41:58.098 --> 42:01.185
you're gonna always
be maintained and sustained.

42:02.019 --> 42:03.437
So we just go with the flow.

42:03.521 --> 42:07.149
Whoever comes through that door
gets the same respect.

42:09.568 --> 42:15.241
I guess with fried chicken, then, or just
soul food in general, too, how to...

42:15.324 --> 42:17.660
If I was, for instance... I see a lot of white guys
making Korean food,

42:20.162 --> 42:22.122
and I'll be honest,
it pisses the shit out of me. 'Cause it's everywhere now.
Kimchi this, kimchi that.

42:24.250 --> 42:27.711
I'm like, "You weren't ostracized
in elementary school,

42:27.795 --> 42:30.881
'cause everyone thought, when they visited
your house, it smelled like garbage."

42:30.965 --> 42:34.677
Right? Like, they didn't have
to endure emotional hardship.

42:34.760 --> 42:37.555
And now it's cool, and...

42:37.638 --> 42:41.267
But when you close your eyes and taste it,
does it always taste like it lacks that?

42:41.350 --> 42:44.395
I can't like it.
It's impossible for me to like.

42:44.478 --> 42:48.482
-I am sorry. I can't like it.
-See, but that...

42:48.566 --> 42:52.444
I will pick that fight with you,
'cause I actually think

42:52.528 --> 42:57.032
that the American experience is actually
an experience of cultural appropriation.

42:57.116 --> 42:58.492
It's what we do best.

42:58.576 --> 43:02.538
We are the greatest mutts
that history ever put together.

43:02.621 --> 43:06.041
And we drag everything
through the collective,

43:06.125 --> 43:10.212
and it comes out different.
We wouldn't have anything without it.

43:18.804 --> 43:21.515
<i>So, we're at the Buford Highway</i>
<i>Farmers Market.</i>

43:21.599 --> 43:24.977
<i>For me and my fellow chefs in Atlanta,</i>
<i>it's like a dream market.</i>

43:26.228 --> 43:29.648
The global world is literally
at your fingertips here.

43:31.817 --> 43:34.737
<i>I never thought that I would have access</i>
<i>to the ingredients</i>

43:34.820 --> 43:36.614
<i>that I have access to today.</i>

43:36.697 --> 43:41.201
It's really a thing of beauty for a chef
who is an immigrant chef like me.

43:42.661 --> 43:45.581
<i>I showcase very regional Indian cuisine.</i>

43:45.664 --> 43:49.293
It's the region that I come from,
which is the southern tip of India.

43:50.169 --> 43:54.632
<i>I was raised Roman Catholic.</i>
<i>I grew up eating beef and pork.</i>

43:54.715 --> 43:57.468
So it's very different
than the natural assumption

43:57.551 --> 43:59.470
that Americans have of Indian cuisine.

44:00.512 --> 44:05.559
So an important part of my fried chicken
recipe is the coconut oil.

44:07.019 --> 44:09.938
<i>I have a lot of herbs</i>
<i>that goes into my brine.</i>

44:10.022 --> 44:14.860
<i>I do a buttermilk brine</i>
<i>with mint, cilantro, green chili.</i>

44:14.943 --> 44:15.944
Ah! Yes.

44:20.949 --> 44:22.534
<i>Every time I make this fried chicken,</i>

44:22.618 --> 44:25.537
people tend to think
it's my Southern American influence,

44:25.621 --> 44:30.334
and I have to let them know
that every culture figured out

44:30.417 --> 44:33.837
if you drenched a bird in flour
and deep fried it,

44:33.921 --> 44:36.632
it was probably gonna be good.

44:36.715 --> 44:41.261
I think everybody has a fried bird,
and this is my mama's fried bird.

44:41.345 --> 44:42.888
Is it always boneless?

44:42.971 --> 44:46.058
I only do boneless,
skinless chicken thigh.

44:46.141 --> 44:47.059
Why?

44:47.142 --> 44:50.229
You tell me if I need
to leave the skin on for next time.

44:50.312 --> 44:51.355
No, I'm excited to try it.

44:53.065 --> 44:54.983
Can I taste the marinade?

44:55.067 --> 44:56.944
Um, it's raw chicken.
-I'm okay.

44:57.027 --> 44:58.320
Okay.

45:00.239 --> 45:02.783
People are probably freaking out
right now, but...

45:02.866 --> 45:04.618
I'm scared of raw chicken.

45:06.870 --> 45:09.581
-That almost tastes like kimchi to me.
Really?

45:09.665 --> 45:11.500
Because of the ginger
and the garlic and the salt.

45:11.583 --> 45:14.336
And it's heavy on the garlic.

45:15.796 --> 45:17.631
That coconut oil is awesome.

45:17.714 --> 45:20.759
It does everything
to this chicken, I'm telling you.

45:20.843 --> 45:25.389
And then this is a mixture
of garam masala, chili and salt.

45:25.472 --> 45:26.932
But if I'm not familiar
with garam masala,

45:27.015 --> 45:29.893
most people will probably think it tastes
like some kind of curry powder, right?

45:29.977 --> 45:32.729
-Exactly, and it's not.
-But it's not.

45:32.813 --> 45:35.524
We don't have anything
called curry powder in India.

45:35.607 --> 45:38.277
I'm so excited.

45:42.114 --> 45:43.073
-Mmm.
-Oh, yeah!

45:43.157 --> 45:44.908
That's so good.

45:44.992 --> 45:50.581
Man, boy, slow down.
The chicken dead, it ain't going nowhere.

45:50.664 --> 45:55.377
This is really unique.
Have you ever tasted anything like this?

45:55.461 --> 45:58.630
-I have not.
-All Kerala, all the way here.

45:58.714 --> 46:00.757
I did not expect this.
It's very good.

46:00.841 --> 46:04.094
I'm gonna try really hard
not to steal any ideas.

46:05.471 --> 46:07.764
<i>I always say, </i>
<i>what I put on a plate</i>

46:07.848 --> 46:09.766
<i>is the sum total </i>
<i>of my life experience, right?</i>

46:09.850 --> 46:13.228
You know, don't call my food "fusion."
I hate that word.

46:13.312 --> 46:14.771
It's the other F word.

46:14.855 --> 46:18.984
Let me ask you this though, 'cause you're
doing all this cooking in Atlanta.

46:19.067 --> 46:21.945
Which calls itself
something "the New South,"

46:22.029 --> 46:24.031
the sort of international South.

46:24.114 --> 46:25.699
Do you see that? Do you see the sense of

46:25.782 --> 46:29.536
other countries and cultures
coming to land and prosper here?

46:30.537 --> 46:34.583
Absolutely. Yeah, I see it among
my fellow American chefs

46:34.666 --> 46:37.377
in the way their cooking
has been influenced.

46:37.461 --> 46:41.757
This is where it is good
to have some authenticity, right?

46:41.840 --> 46:45.010
'Cause I'm always, like, trying
to push any boundary,

46:45.093 --> 46:49.389
but at some point
there's too much mixture, right?

46:49.473 --> 46:52.184
-We are there.
-I think it's about telling a story.

46:52.267 --> 46:54.144
It's great if it's supporting it,

46:54.228 --> 46:57.856
but if people can't own the story,
then I think it loses its power.

47:04.863 --> 47:06.823
<i>Salare is its own identity now.</i>

47:06.907 --> 47:10.285
<i>It is me, but how do I top Salare?</i>

47:10.369 --> 47:13.372
<i>And how do I present myself</i>
<i>to the fullest?</i>

47:13.455 --> 47:14.831
<i>My Southern roots </i>
<i>just kept calling, saying,</i>

47:14.915 --> 47:16.458
<i>"All right, let's do </i>
<i>a Southern restaurant. </i>

47:16.542 --> 47:18.168
<i>Let's do a Southern Restaurant."</i>

47:18.252 --> 47:21.380
Ended up finding this space that
became available right down the street.

47:21.463 --> 47:24.132
What I did is I named it, actually,
after my father.

47:24.216 --> 47:26.969
It's called Junebaby.
And so this is my new baby here.

47:29.137 --> 47:31.848
<i>One of the things</i>
<i>that's been striking to me</i>

47:31.932 --> 47:36.186
is that so many of the emblematic
Southern chefs now are white.

47:36.270 --> 47:38.397
That was honestly
one of the driving forces

47:38.480 --> 47:41.483
which made me want to open up Junebaby.

47:41.567 --> 47:44.486
<i>I noticed that a lot of people of color </i>
<i>who did all the cooking </i>

47:44.570 --> 47:45.946
<i>were forgotten about.</i>

47:46.029 --> 47:47.990
And now Southern food became popular

47:48.073 --> 47:51.493
<i>because white chefs</i>
<i>were cooking Southern food.</i>

47:51.577 --> 47:55.747
I'm like, "What happened
to the Willie Mae's and the Chase?"

47:58.792 --> 48:00.502
<i>Why aren't they getting</i>
<i>that same highlight</i>

48:00.586 --> 48:03.046
as these new up and coming
hipster stars

48:03.130 --> 48:06.008
cooking the food
we've been cooking for years?

48:06.091 --> 48:08.510
It's important to know our history.

48:08.594 --> 48:10.262
Let's talk about it, let's celebrate it.

48:11.179 --> 48:14.975
<i>To understand, like, this food</i>
<i>is built on the struggle.</i>

48:16.893 --> 48:19.813
So these have been soaking overnight,
12 to 16 hours.

48:19.896 --> 48:21.898
A little bit of buttermilk and salt.

48:21.982 --> 48:26.153
<i>You told me that y'all only do</i>
<i>fried chicken on Sunday night.</i>

48:26.236 --> 48:30.073
But the roots of it starts with
West African slaves coming over,

48:30.157 --> 48:33.327
<i>cooking it in palm oil over an open fire.</i>

48:33.410 --> 48:35.162
<i>It didn't happen every day.</i>

48:35.245 --> 48:37.080
<i>And these franchised restaurants</i>
<i>make us assume</i>

48:37.164 --> 48:39.333
<i>that fried chicken</i>
<i>can be enjoyed every day.</i>

48:39.416 --> 48:44.004
And it shouldn't be, but it's delicious
and you want to be enjoying it.

48:45.255 --> 48:47.466
<i>Seems like </i>
<i>you got two missions here.</i>

48:47.549 --> 48:48.800
<i>You're trying to serve people</i>
<i>food they like,</i>

48:48.884 --> 48:51.595
<i>but it also looks like</i>
<i>you're trying to educate people.</i>

48:51.678 --> 48:54.348
I'm not trying to be like a teacher
or a political activist

48:54.431 --> 48:56.016
for Southern food right now.

48:56.099 --> 48:59.436
If it happens, it happens,
but I want to be able to cook good food.

48:59.519 --> 49:01.229
I want to be able to tell the story on it,

49:01.313 --> 49:03.940
so that people can understand
the significance of it.

49:04.024 --> 49:07.736
I'm tripping on seeing tweezers
in the kitchen these days as well.

49:07.819 --> 49:10.364
It's just to toss and turn,
but we don't do tweezer work.

49:10.447 --> 49:12.949
That was that fine dining
that I started out with.

49:13.033 --> 49:16.995
<i>As I found myself, I knew I actually</i>
<i>didn't want to be a tweezer restaurant.</i>

49:17.079 --> 49:20.916
<i>There's no plucking.</i>
<i>We cooking food for flavor here.</i>

49:25.629 --> 49:27.464
<i>I guess I am living up to tradition,</i>

49:27.547 --> 49:29.424
<i>cooking fried chicken,</i>
<i>Southern restaurant.</i>

49:29.508 --> 49:30.967
I'm gonna live up
to tradition eating it.

49:31.051 --> 49:32.177
You're damn right you should.

49:32.260 --> 49:36.139
All right, all right.
I'm going for the wings.

49:36.223 --> 49:37.557
I'm going for the thigh.

49:39.309 --> 49:42.646
Whoo! That's juicy. Did you see that?
It's all over me.

49:42.729 --> 49:46.983
Oh, man. I was too busy listening
to the music of the crust.

49:49.444 --> 49:50.445
Mmm-hmm.

49:51.905 --> 49:53.073
-Oh, yeah.
-Mmm-hmm.

49:54.032 --> 49:55.242
I'm happy with that.

49:55.325 --> 49:56.660
-Mmm-hmm.
-Mmm-hmm.

50:02.791 --> 50:04.751
<i>We've come full circle.</i>

50:05.502 --> 50:07.713
Things African American
are being appreciated

50:07.796 --> 50:09.673
in ways that they haven't been before.

50:11.675 --> 50:13.260
<i>The hope is that we can realize</i>

50:13.343 --> 50:15.762
<i>that we can embrace</i>
<i>each other across our differences,</i>

50:15.846 --> 50:17.973
<i>and not necessarily use these things</i>

50:18.056 --> 50:21.143
<i>as cudgels to beat each other</i>
<i>over the head.</i>

50:21.226 --> 50:23.311
<i>What would you like to see happen</i>

50:23.395 --> 50:27.649
with these powerful subjects in food
with black culture?

50:27.733 --> 50:29.192
Do you want them to...

50:29.276 --> 50:32.404
Is the goal eventually
they'll just go away?

50:32.487 --> 50:35.115
What I really want is for people,
African American people in particular,

50:35.198 --> 50:37.159
to not be ashamed of their histories.

50:37.242 --> 50:39.161
<i>We tend to want to bury it.</i>

50:39.244 --> 50:44.040
<i>And yet, it's the root of everything</i>
<i>that we experience in today's society.</i>

50:46.460 --> 50:49.546
<i>It's this harmless little bird</i>

50:51.173 --> 50:54.968
<i>that is packed with some horrific stuff.</i>

51:00.348 --> 51:03.143
The three of us understand
some things about this country

51:03.226 --> 51:05.812
most white Americans
cannot teach themselves.

51:05.896 --> 51:09.941
The idea of the immigrants
defining and redefining America

51:10.025 --> 51:12.486
<i>has been going on</i>
<i>since at least the 1600s,</i>

51:12.569 --> 51:15.489
when the British first came here
without no goddamn papers,

51:15.572 --> 51:17.407
and nobody arrested their ass.

51:17.491 --> 51:18.366
Preach.

51:19.201 --> 51:20.368
Go on and get that spicy piece.

51:20.452 --> 51:22.412
I know you want
that last spicy piece. Go ahead.

51:23.622 --> 51:25.081
It's like...

51:25.749 --> 51:29.628
<i>My passion for Southern food</i>
<i>is very intense.</i>

51:29.711 --> 51:34.758
<i>And food is the gateway, is the link,</i>
<i>is the connecting piece</i>

51:35.467 --> 51:39.137
<i>that allows people</i>
<i>to share their realities and perspectives.</i>

51:39.221 --> 51:41.807
<i>So, hopefully, the racism...</i>

51:42.849 --> 51:46.186
<i>Hopefully, that behavior changes</i>
<i>when there's more knowledge there,</i>

51:46.269 --> 51:49.981
<i>there's more compassion there,</i>
<i>there's more empathy there.</i>

51:50.941 --> 51:54.152
Everything done here
is done by the heart.

51:54.236 --> 51:58.281
People of all nationalities,
creed, color, origin

51:58.365 --> 52:01.034
break bread together
and be happy together.

52:01.117 --> 52:03.912
<i>Full of love, peace, joy and happiness.</i>

52:05.622 --> 52:09.876
And the best you can do, maybe,
is by using it as inspiration, an homage,

52:09.960 --> 52:11.878
and giving credit where credit is due,

52:11.962 --> 52:16.591
<i>and doing your best to execute the best</i>
<i>goddamn thing you can possibly do.</i>
